Nitpick: Let a method call start and end be at the same indentation level. This convention is used through this repository of code, and adhering to the convention makes it easier to visually walk through code:

```python
        client.post(urljoin(repos[1]['_href'], 'actions/associate/'), {
            'source_repo_id': repos[0]['id'],
            'criteria': {
                'filters': {'unit': {'_id': second_unit_first_repo}},
                'type_ids': ['ostree'],
            },
        })
```

Proposal, not sure if better (I don't like this syntax).

```
const paq = _paq || {};
if (paq.push) { paq.push [...] }
```

@cdeepakroy this was discussed early on. The issue with a dictionary is that it is unordered. If you want to present inputs in a UI, they will be in an unordered jumble if the inputs are a dictionary. If you need to lookup inputs or outputs by name/id, you can always quickly make a map in `O(n)` time and then to quick lookups.

Also, I don't see input and output lists being long enough that `O(n)` lookups will cause any sort of overall performance issue.

So that's the rationale. If there was a good way to create convenience method that would help ease this I'd be all for it. There was some work on a Pythonic dict subclass for Girder Worker tasks that could have convenience methods like this - perhaps we could revisit that.

